            <div type="apparatus">
                <listApp>
                <app n="1">
                    <note>Macalister (1940, 200) read:</note>        
                    <rdg source="MAC1940"><lb/>Ogham: VUN[I]MSETTOR BRE[---EN]N</rdg>
                    <rdg>
                    <lb n="1"/>Roman: RURTES [I]
                    <lb n="2"/>P IDARNOIN</rdg>
                </app>
                </listApp>
            </div>
            <div type="translation">
                <p>An exact translation of the inscription cannot be readily determined.</p>
            </div>
            <div type="commentary">
<p>Although Macalister (1940, 198) supplied a suggested segmented reading of the inscription, he did not offer any interpretation, noting that the ogham is <q>very difficult and requires prolonged study</q>. John Borland of the HES prepared a drawing of the supposed ogham but did not offer a reading (see <ref target="https://www.trove.scot/image/1081380">Trove</ref>). The OG(H)AM project visited the stone in 2022 and could not discern a convincing ogham.</p>
                <p>Regarding the roman text, however, Macalister (ibid.) linked IDARNOIN with the EDDARRNONN of the Scoonie stone (S-FIF-001) and IP to the IPE on the Drosten Stone from St Vigeans.</p>
            </div>
